Easily distinguished from known congeners by male clypeus modification (shapes of pair of apophyses; 
Fig. 29
), male palp (shapes of procursus and bulbal process; 
Figs 70, 71
), and distinctive epigynum (large pits and lateral processes; 
Figs 30
, 
62
, 
73
).

COLOR. Carapace ochre-yellow, medially slightly darker including ocular area and clypeus, sternum light brown with slightly darker radiating marks, legs ochre-yellow with many small black marks, mostly on femora (
Fig. 28
) and tibiae, not on coxae, few on metatarsi, abdomen ochre-grey with indistinct small dark and white internal marks dorsally and laterally, ventrally with darker pattern, wider anterior of gonopore.

Known from Yemen and from several localities in Kenya, Rift Valley Province (
Fig. 19
).
